# Images vs. containers

Two everyday words, **not** the same thing.

## Image = the template

A frozen, **read-only** snapshot of a filesystem + metadata. It doesn't *do* anything — a blueprint. Like a **class**.

## Container = a running instance

Created from an image, with its own state + a thin **writable layer** on top. Like an **object**.

| | Image | Container |
|---|---|---|
| OOP | class | object |
| Cooking | recipe | the dish |
| Software | installer | running program |

## The verbs follow the split

- **build** / **pull** an *image*
- **run** an image → a *container*
- **stop** · **start** · **rm** *containers*

**One image, many containers** — they share the read-only layers on disk, so 10 containers cost almost nothing extra. Copy-on-write layering is why containers are cheap.
